<br>
Correct me if I'm wrong, but I'm fairly positive there isn't much education regarding Australian *anything* over in the good ol' US of A.  So don't feel bad, Zoit; the ignorance goes both ways.<br>
<br>
FYI, we learn Australian history, with a touch of English history (and in my case Mediaeval and Classical also, but they were electives) and it may surprise you to know that American history isn't really considered terribly important.<br>
<br>
Perhaps it has something to do with the fact that we were settled primarily by the British?  Perhaps it's because we have our own indigenous peoples to learn about.  Perhaps it is because we're a relatively young country and the teething problems the US went through simply weren't relevant to our situation.<br>
<br>
I'm sure there are any number of reasons for US history being overlooked, but you can take heart because Didi and I are attempting to make up for the grievous oversights of our school system via this marvellous interactive educational tool right here. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
